  <main>

    <a href="/reading/game-theory/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to game theory</a>

    <h1>Prisoner's Dilemma and Chicken</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Nordstrom, <em>Introduction to Game Theory</em> · <a href="https://nordstrommath.com/IntroGameTheory/pdandchicken.html">Section 4.2</a> · CC BY-SA 4.0</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">The two most famous non-zero-sum games. In the <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prisoner%27s_dilemma"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Prisoner's Dilemma</a></strong>, defecting dominates but mutual cooperation pays better. In <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicken_(game)"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Chicken</a></strong>, swerving is safe but going straight wins if the other swerves. Both show how individual rationality can produce collective irrationality.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Two 2x2 matrices side by side -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 640 230" class="w-full max-w-2xl" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
